# Component & Store Decomposition

## Self-Managed Cards

Card components receive `repoPath` as their primary prop and manage their own data and actions internally. They should **never** receive large lists of callback props from a parent.

```tsx
// BAD: parent passes data + 15 handler props
<StashesCard stashes={stashes} onStash={...} onApply={...} onDelete={...} onView={...} />

// GOOD: card reads its own data and uses domain hooks
<StashesCard repoPath={repoPath} />
```

## Zustand Repository Store Selectors (CRITICAL)

`updateRepoCache` spreads the existing cache (`{ ...existing, ...data }`), creating a **new object reference** every time ANY field changes. Selectors that return the whole cache object cause every subscribed component to re-render on every update — even unrelated ones like a checkbox toggling `selectedStagedChanges`.

### In components that RENDER data: use specific field selectors

```tsx
// Stable empty default at module level (outside the component)
const _EMPTY_ARR: any[] = [];

// BAD: re-renders on ANY cache field change (causes multi-second UI freezes)
const repoCache = useRepositoryStore((s) => s.getCacheFor(repoPath));
const stashes = useMemo(() => repoCache?.stashes || [], [repoCache?.stashes]);

// GOOD: only re-renders when `stashes` reference actually changes
const stashes = useRepositoryStore((s) => s.repoCache[repoPath]?.stashes) ?? _EMPTY_ARR;
```

Use a module-level `_EMPTY_ARR` / `_EMPTY_OBJ` constant as the fallback so `??` returns a stable reference when the field is undefined.

### In hooks that only read cache in callbacks: use imperative `getState()`

When a hook only reads cache data inside `useCallback` handlers (not during render), don't subscribe at all — use `getState()` for zero re-renders:

```ts
// BAD: subscribes to entire cache, triggers re-renders, only to feed a ref
const repoCache = useRepositoryStore((s) => s.getCacheFor(repoPath));
const repoCacheRef = useRef(repoCache);
repoCacheRef.current = repoCache;
// ... later in a callback: repoCacheRef.current?.stashes

// GOOD: no subscription, no re-renders, always fresh data
const getCache = () => useRepositoryStore.getState().repoCache[repoPath];
// ... later in a callback: getCache()?.stashes
```

### For derived/content-based keys: compute inside the selector

When you need a stable value derived from array contents (e.g., for `useEffect` deps), compute it inside the selector so Zustand's `Object.is` check returns a stable string:

```ts
const stagedKey = useRepositoryStore((state) => {
  const arr = state.repoCache[repoPath]?.changes?.stagedChanges;
  if (!arr || arr.length === 0) return '';
  return arr.map((c: any) => `${c.file}:${c.change}`).join(',');
});
```

## Domain Hooks

Group related handlers into a single hook per domain (e.g. `useBranchActions`, `useStagingActions`). Hooks interact with stores directly -- consumers don't need to know which stores are involved.

- One hook per domain, not per card. Hooks may be shared across cards.
- Hooks accept `repoPath` and return stable callbacks via `useCallback`.
- Prefer `getState()` over reactive subscriptions when data is only read inside callbacks.

## Shared View State (`repoViewStore`)

State that multiple cards need to read/write (diff view, commit message, active operation) lives in `repoViewStore`, keyed by `repoPath`. Cards that only own local UI state (filters, expanded items) keep it as `useState`.

- Per-repo keying: `state.showDiff[repoPath]`, not global `state.showDiff`.
- Use `store.getState()` inside callbacks to avoid stale closures.
- Granular selectors: `useRepoViewStore((s) => s.commitMessage[repoPath])`.

## Feature-Owned Modals

Modals belong to the feature that triggers them, not a central parent. `LocalBranchesCard` renders its own create/rename/delete branch modals. `StashesCard` renders its own create stash modal.

## Layout Shell

`RepoView` is a thin layout component (~120 lines). It only handles:
- Lifecycle (`useRepoLifecycle`)
- Section layout and drag-drop (`useSectionLayout`)
- Composing self-managed card components with `repoPath`
